## 3. Technique-by-Technique Breakdown

* Serve
    * Produces heavy, loaded spins with crisp contact. Excellent for fast, deep serves due to the high-tension topsheet.

* Receive
    * Push/Stop: Controllable and stays low.
    * Flick/Flip: Requires an active, aggressive stroke.
    * Chiquita/Banana: Devastatingly fast and spinny, provided the player has the wrist speed to activate the rubber.

* Loop/Drive
    * First Loop (3rd Ball): Needs good body mechanics; cannot rely on the rubber to do the work.
    * Continuous Looping: Rewards a rhythmic, full-swing loop with heavy pressure on the opponent.
    * Power Loop / Kill: The rubber's absolute best feature. Flat-out kills are laser-like and virtually unreturnable.

* Countering
    * Counter-Topspin: Supremely stable. The hard sponge eats incoming energy and fires it back with interest.
    * Punch Counter / Active Block: Very effective and fast, turning defense into offense instantly.

* Blocking
    * Passive Block: Solid, though it requires a firm wrist to handle incoming heavy spin due to the grippy topsheet.
    * Active Block: Highly rewarding, allowing for fast, redirective placements.

* Smash & Flat Hit
    * Surprisingly crisp. The firm sponge provides a stable base for flat kills, lacking the mushiness of softer rubbers.

* Defense (If Relevant)
    * Chop: [Inference] Possible but difficult due to the catapult effect at higher impacts and extreme spin sensitivity.
    * Lob/Fish: Deep and spinny, allowing players to buy time from far off the table.

